                <!-- Featured Article -->
                <section id="featured" class="content-section featured-article">
                    <div class="section-header">
                        <span class="section-tag">FEATURED STORY</span>
                        <h2>The Ultimate Guide to Winter Yacht Storage in the Mediterranean</h2>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="featured-image">🛥️</div>
                    
                    <div class="article-content">
                        <p><strong>As winter approaches, yacht owners face critical decisions about storing their vessels in the Mediterranean.</strong> With over 25 years of experience managing yacht fleets across the region, I've learned that proper winter storage can mean the difference between a $50,000 maintenance bill and smooth sailing come spring.</p>

                        <h3>Why Mediterranean Winter Storage Matters</h3>
                        <p>The Mediterranean might seem mild compared to northern climates, but winter storms can reach Force 10 conditions, with waves exceeding 6 meters. Even in supposedly protected harbors, I've witnessed significant damage to improperly prepared vessels. Last winter alone, insurance claims in the Western Mediterranean exceeded €120 million due to storm damage.</p>

                        <div class="highlight-box">
                            <h4>🌊 Key Mediterranean Winter Challenges:</h4>
                            <ul style="list-style: none; padding-left: 0;">
                                <li>• Sudden medicanes (Mediterranean hurricanes) with winds up to 120 km/h</li>
                                <li>• Severe humidity causing mold and electrical issues</li>
                                <li>• Temperature fluctuations damaging gel coat and teak</li>
                                <li>• Increased theft risk in less-supervised marinas</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>

                        <h3>Top 5 Winter Storage Locations Reviewed</h3>
                        
                        <h4>1. Port Vauban, Antibes, France</h4>
                        <p>The gold standard for superyacht winter storage. With 1,642 berths including 19 for yachts over 100m, Port Vauban offers unparalleled protection and services. Their specialized winter care program includes weekly inspections, engine runs, and climate control systems.</p>
                        <p><strong>Cost:</strong> €800-2,500/meter/month | <strong>Security:</strong> 24/7 patrol + CCTV | <strong>Rating:</strong> ★★★★★</p>

                        <h4>2. Marina di Portofino, Italy</h4>
                        <p>Exclusive and protected, this marina offers personalized winter care packages. Limited to 550 berths, ensuring attention to detail. The natural harbor provides excellent storm protection.</p>
                        <p><strong>Cost:</strong> €600-1,800/meter/month | <strong>Security:</strong> Excellent | <strong>Rating:</strong> ★★★★★</p>

                        <h4>3. Port Adriano, Mallorca</h4>
                        <p>Philippe Starck-designed marina with state-of-the-art facilities. Excellent technical support and a full-service shipyard on-site for winter work.</p>
                        <p><strong>Cost:</strong> €400-1,200/meter/month | <strong>Security:</strong> Very Good | <strong>Rating:</strong> ★★★★☆</p>

                        <h4>4. Karpaz Gate Marina, Cyprus</h4>
                        <p>Emerging as a popular winter destination with competitive rates and excellent weather. Full haul-out facilities and covered storage options available.</p>
                        <p><strong>Cost:</strong> €250-700/meter/month | <strong>Security:</strong> Good | <strong>Rating:</strong> ★★★★☆</p>

                        <h4>5. Marina Barcelona 92, Spain</h4>
                        <p>Urban location with excellent access to services and crew. Strong winter maintenance infrastructure but exposed to easterly storms.</p>
                        <p><strong>Cost:</strong> €500-1,500/meter/month | <strong>Security:</strong> Very Good | <strong>Rating:</strong> ★★★☆☆</p>

                        <div class="pro-tip">
                            <div class="pro-tip-header">💡 PRO TIP</div>
                            <p>Book your winter berth by August for best rates and availability. Many premium marinas offer 15-20% early bird discounts, potentially saving tens of thousands on larger yachts.</p>
                        </div>

                        <h3>Essential Winter Preparation Checklist</h3>
                        
                        <h4>Hull & Exterior</h4>
                        <p>Begin with a thorough haul-out inspection. Look for osmosis signs, especially on older GRP hulls. Apply a fresh coat of antifouling if staying in water. For boats over 20m, consider a full polish and ceramic coating application - the €5,000-15,000 investment protects against winter UV damage and makes spring commissioning easier.</p>

                        <h4>Engine & Mechanical Systems</h4>
                        <p>Change all fluids before storage - old oil becomes acidic over winter. Run engines to operating temperature with fresh oil, then fog cylinders if storing for over 3 months. Diesel bug proliferates in winter; add biocide and fill tanks to 95% to minimize condensation.</p>

                        <h4>Interior Climate Control</h4>
                        <p>Mediterranean humidity is a silent destroyer. Install multiple dehumidifiers (calculate 1 unit per 15m² minimum). Set to maintain 50-55% humidity. Lower risks mold; higher causes wood cracking. Smart WiFi-enabled units allow remote monitoring - essential for absentee owners.</p>

                        <div class="market-card">
                            <h4>⚡ Cost-Saving Alert</h4>
                            <p>Running dehumidifiers 24/7 can cost €300-500/month in electricity. Invest in solar panels (€3,000-8,000 for a 50-footer) to offset costs. Most Mediterranean marinas now allow solar installations, with ROI typically under 2 years.</p>
                        </div>

                        <h4>Security Measures</h4>
                        <p>Winter attracts opportunistic theft. Remove all electronics not hard-wired. Install motion-activated cameras (4G models like Reolink Go for €200 send instant alerts). Consider a GPS tracker hidden in the bilge - recovery rate for stolen yachts with trackers exceeds 85%.</p>

                        <h3>The Insurance Factor</h3>
                        <p>Most policies require specific winter precautions for coverage validity. Document everything with photos. Some insurers offer 10-15% discounts for approved storage locations. Pantaenius and Towergate have excellent Mediterranean winter programs worth investigating.</p>

                        <h3>Alternative: Live-Aboard Winter Cruising</h3>
                        <p>Why store when you can explore? The Eastern Mediterranean offers fantastic winter cruising. Turkey's Turquoise Coast, Greek Ionian islands, and Egypt's Red Sea provide warm weather and empty anchorages. Many marinas offer "winter afloat" packages with significant discounts for 3-6 month stays.</p>

                        <div class="highlight-box">
                            <h4>📍 Top Winter Cruising Destinations:</h4>
                            <ul style="list-style: none; padding-left: 0;">
                                <li>• <strong>Turkish Riviera:</strong> 15-20°C, excellent marinas, 60% off-season discounts</li>
                                <li>• <strong>Canary Islands:</strong> 18-24°C, Atlantic sailing, duty-free fuel</li>
                                <li>• <strong>Malta:</strong> 14-18°C, English-speaking, EU facilities</li>
                                <li>• <strong>Cyprus:</strong> 16-22°C, year-round sailing, low costs</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>

                        <h3>Final Thoughts from the Helm</h3>
                        <p>After decades in the industry, I've seen too many owners treat winter storage as an afterthought, leading to expensive spring surprises. Whether you choose premium storage in Antibes or budget-friendly options in Cyprus, the key is preparation and regular monitoring.</p>

                        <p>Remember: A yacht is a living, breathing entity that needs attention even when dormant. The €5,000-10,000 invested in proper winter care saves multiples in prevented damage and maintains resale value. As we say in the trade, "Winter care is spring peace of mind."</p>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <!-- Maintenance Guide -->
                <section id="maintenance" class="content-section">
                    <div class="section-header">
                        <span class="section-tag">TECHNICAL DEEP DIVE</span>
                        <h2>DIY Watermaker Maintenance: Save €3,000 Annually</h2>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="article-content">
                        <p>Watermakers are notoriously finicky, but with proper maintenance, they're remarkably reliable. Most service calls I see are entirely preventable with basic owner maintenance.</p>

                        <h4>The 30-Minute Weekly Routine</h4>
                        <p>Every Sunday morning, while your coffee brews, perform these checks:</p>
                        
                        <div class="tip-card">
                            <span class="tip-number">1</span>
                            <strong>Pressure Check:</strong> High-pressure gauge should read within 5% of baseline. Dropping pressure indicates filter clogging or pump wear.
                        </div>

                        <div class="tip-card">
                            <span class="tip-number">2</span>
                            <strong>Pre-Filter Inspection:</strong> 5-micron pre-filter should be cream-colored. Brown indicates organics; replace immediately (€25 vs €2,500 membrane damage).
                        </div>

                        <div class="tip-card">
                            <span class="tip-number">3</span>
                            <strong>Product Water TDS Test:</strong> Should read <500ppm. Gradual increase signals membrane aging. Sudden spike means immediate attention needed.
                        </div>

                        <div class="tip-card">
                            <span class="tip-number">4</span>
                            <strong>Listen & Feel:</strong> Unusual vibrations or sounds often precede failures by weeks. That new clicking? Probably a check valve beginning to fail (€45 part, €500 service call).
                        </div>

                        <h4>The Flush Debate: Fresh vs Salt</h4>
                        <p>Industry consensus has shifted. For boats used weekly, salt water flushing is sufficient. For gaps over 5 days, fresh water flush is mandatory. Over 30 days? Biocide treatment or pickling is essential. I've seen €8,000 membranes destroyed by biofilm in just 6 weeks of neglect.</p>

                        <div class="pro-tip">
                            <div class="pro-tip-header">⚙️ TECH TIP</div>
                            <p>Install a carbon block post-filter (€150) even if your water tastes fine. It removes chlorine that damages membranes during fresh water flushes, extending membrane life by 30-40%.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

