        <section class="content-section" style="margin-top: 40px;">
            <div class="section-header">
                <span class="section-tag">FROM THE DOCK</span>
                <h2>Reader Questions Answered</h2>
            </div>
            
            <div class="article-content">
                <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 20px;">
                    <p style="font-style: italic; margin-bottom: 15px;">"My 2019 Beneteau Oceanis 51.1 has developed small spider cracks around the chain plates. The dealer says it's cosmetic, but I'm concerned. Should I be worried?" - Robert, Portsmouth</p>
                    <p><strong>Captain's Answer:</strong> Robert, you're right to be concerned. While hairline cracks in gel coat are often cosmetic, cracks around chain plates demand immediate attention. These are high-stress areas where cosmetic quickly becomes structural. Have an independent surveyor check with a moisture meter - if readings exceed 20%, you have water ingress. Given it's a 2019, you're still under Beneteau's 5-year structural warranty. Document everything with photos and push for proper repair, not just cosmetic filling.</p>
                </div>

                <div style="background: #f8fafc; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 20px;">
                    <p style="font-style: italic; margin-bottom: 15px;">"I'm considering switching from traditional antifoul to Coppercoat. Is it worth the €8,000 investment for my 45-footer?" - Maria, Palma</p>
                    <p><strong>Captain's Answer:</strong> Maria, Coppercoat can be excellent, but success depends on preparation quality and your usage pattern. If you're sailing regularly (2+ times monthly), it performs brilliantly for 8-10 years. For boats sitting idle, traditional biocide-based antifoul often works better. In Palma's warm waters, ensure the applicator is certified - I've seen many DIY disasters. Pro tip: Negotiate application during winter haul-out when yards need work. You might save 20-30% off that €8,000 quote.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Adventure Story -->
        <section class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
                <span class="section-tag">ADVENTURE LOG</span>
                <h2>Lessons from a Force 10 Storm in the Aegean</h2>
            </div>
            
            <div class="article-content">
                <p>Three weeks ago, delivering a Hanse 548 from Athens to Malta, we encountered an unforecast medicane that taught me lessons no amount of experience can prepare you for...</p>
                
                <p>The morning started perfectly - 15 knots from the northwest, flat seas, making 8 knots under full sail. The forecast showed a mild front passing through overnight. By 1400, the barometer had dropped 8mb in two hours. That's when I knew we were in trouble.</p>

                <p>Within three hours, we were facing 50-knot sustained winds with gusts over 65. Seas built to 7 meters with breaking crests. The autopilot gave up at 2300. Hand-steering in those conditions tested every ounce of seamanship...</p>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4>Key Lessons Learned:</h4>
                    <ul style="padding-left: 20px;">
                        <li>Trust your barometer over forecasts - rapid pressure drops don't lie</li>
                        <li>Series drogues work - ours likely saved the boat</li>
                        <li>Practice heavy weather tactics in moderate conditions</li>
                        <li>Crew fatigue is the biggest danger - rotate every hour maximum</li>
                        <li>Modern weather routing still misses Mediterranean mini-cyclones</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <p>Full story with lessons learned available in our premium member area...</p>
            </div>
        </section>
